   of hot-Jupiters and that of their parent stars.
   Aims. We propose a method that allows the characterization of the
   adopted C/O ratio in protoplanetary disks independently from the
   determination of the host star composition. Titanium and vanadium
   chemistries are investigated because they are strong optical absorbers
   and also because their oxides are known to be sensitive to the C/O ratio
   in some exoplanet atmospheres.
   Methods. We use a commercial package based on the Gibbs energy
   minimization technique to compute the titanium and vanadium equilibrium
   chemistries in protoplanetary disks for C/O ratios ranging from 0.05 to
   10. Our calculations are performed for pressures in the 10(-6)-10(-2)
   bar domain, and for temperatures ranging from 50 K to 2000 K.
   Results. We find that the vanadium nitride/vanadium oxide and titanium
   hydride/titanium oxide gas phase ratios strongly depend on the C/O ratio
   in the hot parts of disks (T >= 1000 K). Our calculations suggest that,
   in these regions, these ratios can be used as tracers of the C/O value
   in protoplanetary disks.}},
DOI = {{10.1051/0004-6361/201321780}},
Article-Number = {A60}}

